	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Memblers</b> [ Tue Aug 03, 2010 6:35 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">jbbenz wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Basic knowledge of hardware i guess i can start there!  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_biggrin.gif" alt=":D" title="Very Happy" />  can you direct me as to a site or more information were i can start off??<br />I looked into the CopyNES but he states on his site that it is not ment for play back!<br />Thankx</div>
<br />
<br />I don't know any sites in particular, look up address decoding, figure out how parallel memories like EPROM and SRAM work, how the 6502 address and data bus work (PPU is similar but separate), then you would have to wire something up to read it all.  But it won't work with much, until you read up on every kind of mapper and board type and add support for it.  And you need software to do the reading.
<br />
<br />I guess the Retrode has a microcontroller in it, which would be pretty good for this.  In that case you need to know the programming language the microcontroller uses (and all the needed hardware it has).  You also need a way to interface it to the PC.
<br />
<br />I guess if you consider the EPROM / CPU stuff basic (I think it is), then there isn't much hardware knowledge needed.  But there's a decent amount of software (and/or firmware) involved.
<br />
<br />Using CopyNES would just be a lot easier.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


